Question 5.

We do not make a graph of Species as it mainly serves as an identifier/label. Graphing it would provide no useful information as we would only see each specie marked once and not get any identifiable trends across the species.

Question 6.

Making a graph of variable Status. We will be making a bar chart as we only have one categorical variable (the status of the bird) to present and no quantitative variable. Bar charts make it easy to contrast the different levels within the categorical variable.

ggplot(Island_bird_data, aes(x = Status)) + geom_bar()

The graph shows us that the data set observes more than twice as many resident bird species than migratory bird species.

Question 7.

We will be making a graph for the variable Pairs. We will be making a histogram as we have one quantitative variable and no categorical variable. A histogram allows us to not only see the data but also its spread.

ggplot(Island_bird_data, aes(x = Pairs)) + geom_histogram(bins = 6)

The graph shows us that the data has slight skew to the right. This means that while most islands have a small number of pairs (0-4), some islands have an unusually high number (8-12).

Question 8.

We need to graph one Categorical Variable (Size) and one quantitative variable (Pairs) so we will use side by side box-plots.

ggplot(Island_bird_data, aes(x = Size, y = Pairs)) + geom_boxplot()

The graph shows us that there are, on average, the same number of pairs of large birds as there are small bird pairs. There is greater variation in size within the smaller pairs.

Question 9.

We now have to graph two quantitative variables (Pairs and extinction time) so we will use a scatter-plot. I will plot a regression line to confirm if there is correlation between the variables.

ggplot(Island_bird_data, aes(x = Pairs, y = Time)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

The graph shows us that there is a positive correlation (albeit weak) between number of pairs and the extinction time/longevity of the bird species survival. We see that this correlation becomes weaker as the number of pairs increases suggesting that some other factor might be differentiating them.

Question 10.

We now have two categorical variables (Size and status) and no quantitative variables to graph so we will use grouped bar charts.

 ggplot(Island_bird_data, aes(x = Status, fill = Size)) + geom_bar(position = "dodge")

We can see from the graph that the size split between migratory and resident bird species is approximately the same but that there are significantly more birds of each size that are residents.

Question 11.

We now need to graph one categorical (Size) and two quantitative variables (Extinction time and pairs) so we will use scatter-plot with points identified by group (in this case, colour)

ggplot(Island_bird_data, aes(x = Pairs, y = Time , colour = Size )) + geom_point()

From this graph, we can note that while there is a positive correlation between number of pairs and extinction time (as was seen prior as well), we can also note that the smaller pairs seem to be lasting longer than the larger pairs, therefore hinting that size maybe playing a role in their survival.
